  "local_port": 38192,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I cook manchurian?",
  "response": "Manchurian is a popular Indo-Chinese dish that comes in various forms, such as **Vegetable Manchurian** and **Chicken Manchurian**. Below are detailed recipes for both versions. You can choose the one that suits your preference!\n\n---\n\n## Vegetable Manchurian Recipe\n\n### **Ingredients**\n\n#### **For the Manchurian Balls:**\n- **Vegetables:**\n  - 1 cup finely chopped cabbage\n  - 1/2 cup grated carrots\n  - 1/2 cup finely chopped beans (optional)\n  - 1/2 cup finely chopped bell peppers (capsicum)\n- 1/2 cup all-purpose flour (maida)\n- 1/4 cup cornstarch\n- 1 tablespoon soy sauce\n- 1 teaspoon ginger-garlic paste\n- 1-2 green chilies, finely chopped\n- Salt and pepper to taste\n- Oil for frying\n\n#### **For the Sauce:**\n- 2 tablespoons oil\n- 1 tablespoon finely chopped garlic\n- 1 tablespoon finely chopped ginger\n- 2-3 green chilies, slit or chopped\n- 1 medium onion, finely chopped\n- 1/2 cup bell peppers, chopped into cubes\n- 2 tablespoons soy sauce\n- 1 tablespoon chili sauce (adjust to taste)\n- 1 tablespoon tomato ketchup\n- 1/2 teaspoon vinegar\n- 1 cup water or vegetable broth\n- 1 tablespoon cornstarch mixed with 2 tablespoons water (slurry)\n- Salt and pepper to taste\n- Spring onions for garnish\n\n### **Instructions**\n\n#### **1. Prepare the Manchurian Balls:**\n   - **Combine Vegetables:** In a large mixing bowl, combine the finely chopped cabbage, grated carrots, chopped beans, and bell peppers.\n   - **Add Binding Ingredients:** To the vegetables, add all-purpose flour, cornstarch, soy sauce, ginger-garlic paste, chopped green chilies, salt, and pepper. Mix well until the mixture holds together. If it's too dry, add a little water; if too wet, add more flour.\n   - **Form Balls:** Take small portions of the mixture and shape them into bite-sized balls.\n   - **Fry the Balls:** Heat oil in a deep frying pan or wok over medium heat. Fry the Manchurian balls in batches until they turn golden brown and crispy. Remove and drain on paper towels. Set aside.\n\n#### **2. Prepare the Sauce:**\n   - **Saut\u00e9 Aromatics:** In a separate pan or wok, heat 2 tablespoons of oil over medium heat. Add the chopped garlic, ginger, and green chilies. Saut\u00e9 for about 30 seconds until fragrant.\n   - **Add Vegetables:** Add the chopped onions and bell peppers. Stir-fry for 2-3 minutes until they are slightly tender but still retain some crunch.\n   - **Add Sauces:** Stir in the soy sauce, chili sauce, tomato ketchup, and vinegar. Mix well.\n   - **Add Liquid:** Pour in the water or vegetable broth and bring the mixture to a simmer.\n   - **Thicken the Sauce:** Add the cornstarch slurry to the sauce, stirring continuously to avoid lumps. Cook until the sauce thickens to your desired consistency.\n   - **Season:** Taste and adjust salt and pepper as needed.\n\n#### **3. Combine and Garnish:**\n   - **Add Manchurian Balls:** Gently add the fried Manchurian balls to the sauce. Toss them carefully to coat evenly without breaking them.\n   - **Simmer:** Let the Manchurian simmer in the sauce for 2-3 minutes to absorb the flavors.\n   - **Garnish:** Sprinkle chopped spring onions on top.\n\n### **Serving Suggestions**\n- **With:** Serve hot as an appetizer or as a main dish with fried rice or noodles.\n- **Tip:** For an extra tangy flavor, you can add a dash of lemon juice before serving.\n\n---\n\n## Chicken Manchurian Recipe\n\n### **Ingredients**\n\n#### **For the Chicken Balls:**\n- 500 grams boneless chicken, finely chopped or minced\n- 1/2 cup breadcrumbs or cornflakes, crushed\n- 2 tablespoons all-purpose flour (maida)\n- 1 tablespoon soy sauce\n- 1 tablespoon ginger-garlic paste\n- 1-2 green chilies, finely chopped\n- 1 teaspoon black pepper powder\n- Salt to taste\n- 1 egg (optional, for binding)\n- Oil for frying\n\n#### **For the Sauce:**\n- 2 tablespoons oil\n- 2 tablespoons finely chopped garlic\n- 2 tablespoons finely chopped ginger\n- 3-4 green chilies, slit or chopped\n- 1 medium onion, finely chopped\n- 1/2 cup bell peppers, chopped into cubes\n- 3 tablespoons soy sauce\n- 2 tablespoons chili sauce (adjust to taste)\n- 2 tablespoons tomato ketchup\n- 1 teaspoon vinegar\n- 1.5 cups chicken broth or water\n- 1.5 tablespoons cornstarch mixed with 3 tablespoons water (slurry)\n- Salt and pepper to taste\n- Spring onions for garnish\n\n### **Instructions**\n\n#### **1. Prepare the Chicken Balls:**\n   - **Mix Ingredients:** In a large bowl, combine the minced chicken, crushed breadcrumbs or cornflakes, all-purpose flour, soy sauce, ginger-garlic paste, chopped green chilies, black pepper, and salt. If using, add the egg for better binding.\n   - **Form Balls:** Shape the mixture into small, bite-sized balls. Ensure they are not too large to cook evenly.\n   - **Fry the Balls:** Heat oil in a deep pan or fryer over medium heat. Fry the chicken balls in batches until they are golden brown and fully cooked. Remove and drain on paper towels. Set aside.\n\n#### **2. Prepare the Sauce:**\n   - **Saut\u00e9 Aromatics:** In a wok or large pan, heat 2 tablespoons of oil over medium heat. Add the chopped garlic, ginger, and green chilies. Saut\u00e9 for about 30 seconds until fragrant.\n   - **Add Vegetables:** Add the chopped onions and bell peppers. Stir-fry for 3-4 minutes until they are slightly tender yet crunchy.\n   - **Add Sauces:** Pour in the soy sauce, chili sauce, tomato ketchup, and vinegar. Mix well.\n   - **Add Liquid:** Add the chicken broth or water and bring the mixture to a simmer.\n   - **Thicken the Sauce:** Stir in the cornstarch slurry gradually while continuously stirring to avoid lumps. Cook until the sauce thickens to your desired consistency.\n   - **Season:** Adjust salt and pepper to taste. Remember that soy sauce and other sauces already add saltiness.\n\n#### **3. Combine and Garnish:**\n   - **Add Chicken Balls:** Gently add the fried chicken balls into the sauce. Toss carefully to coat them evenly without breaking.\n   - **Simmer:** Let the Chicken Manchurian simmer in the sauce for about 3-4 minutes so that the flavors meld.\n   - **Garnish:** Sprinkle chopped spring onions on top.\n\n### **Serving Suggestions**\n- **With:** Serve hot as an appetizer or as a main dish accompanied by steamed rice, fried rice, or noodles.\n- **Tip:** For added crunch, you can toss the chicken balls in a little more cornstarch before frying.\n\n---\n\n## Tips for Perfect Manchurian\n\n1. **Texture of Vegetable Manchurian:** To ensure the Manchurian balls hold together, finely chop or grate the vegetables, especially cabbage and carrots. Squeeze out excess water using a clean kitchen towel to prevent sogginess.\n\n2. **Crispy Exterior:** For extra crispy Manchurian balls, high-quality frying oil and maintaining the right oil temperature (around 350\u00b0F or 175\u00b0C) are crucial. Fry in batches to avoid lowering the oil temperature.\n\n3. **Adjusting Spice Levels:** Modify the number of green chilies and the amount of chili sauce according to your heat preference.\n\n4. **Vegan Option:** To make a vegan version, omit eggs in the chicken Manchurian recipe or use plant-based binders.\n\n5. **Consistency of Sauce:** If you prefer a thicker sauce, add more cornstarch slurry. For a thinner sauce, reduce the amount of cornstarch or add more broth/water.\n\n6. **Flavor Enhancements:** Some recipes include adding a splash of sesame oil at the end for added flavor.\n\n---\n\nEnjoy your homemade Manchurian! Whether you choose the vegetable or chicken version, this dish is sure to be a hit with its savory and tangy flavors.",
